In this pack, the goal is to beat the Ender Dragon. This is a nearly impossible task, due to the ridiculous crafting recipes and evil mobs. It is likely that you will die many times in this pack. And by many, I mean thousands.

In order to craft anything, you must get a Crafting Table. Unfortunately, you cannot turn logs into planks, at least with your inventory. Instead, you have to gather many materials so that you can make a Crafting Table.

You will need Coarse Dirt, Red Sand, Clay, and Flint.

§dGood Luck

§d§fYou do §d§c§c§lNOT §fwant to be out at night.

The next step for the player is to craft an Ultimate Crafting Table. Nearly all crafting recipes are 9x9, and require ridiculous amounts of resources, some of which are insanely hard to find. This recipe is a good warmup for future recipes, which will be even more insane.

One component of the Ultimate Crafting Table is a Spider Eye. This is going to be difficult to acquire, although not as hard as some of the more....questionable components selected for the recipe. 

The main challenge associated with this component is the sheer difficulty in killing mobs, as you likely won't have weapons, and the mobs are superbuffed.

Unfortunately for you, this is likely the easiest component to gather.

Another component required is the Ender Pearl. This will be very hard to get, due to the sheer difficulty of killing a superbuffed Enderman. The difficulty is worsened by the fact that Endermen aren't as common as other hostiles, meaning that you will have to brave waves of the other mobs to find an Enderman.

The Music Disc (chirp) is one of the hardest components to get. You have to get a Skeleton to shoot a Creeper to death. The sheer amount of health these beings have will make this take a long time. To make matters worse, you will likely die to either of the monsters' attacks long before they come close to killing each other. 

Your only hope is to weaken the Creeper to the extent that the Skeleton can easily kill it. Even if you are successful, the type of music disc dropped is completely random. There are 12 discs, and only one will work for this recipe.

To add insult to injury, there is no way of knowing the health of a mob by looking at it.

A Diamond is one of the components for the Ultimate Crafting Table. However, you can't acquire one the normal way, due to being unable to craft tools. 

You will need to search for a structure generated in the world, as they may have chests that have a chance of having Diamonds.

You will need a Prismarine Shard in order to craft an Ultimate Crafting Table. In order to do this, you will need to go to an ocean and swim until you find an ocean monument. Then, you will need to kill Guardians until one of them drops a Prismarine Shard.

The most difficult part of this is that you will have to keep an eye on your breath meter, and you can't craft anything to help you restore your breath meter. You will need to loot these blocks from naturally generated structures if you wish to have any chance of survival.

In order to acquire the Totem of Undying, a vital component of the Ultimate Crafting Table, you must travel thousands of blocks away until you find a woodland mansion. You must then find and kill the Evoker, which will drop a Totem of Undying.

While the Totem of Undying can be used to save you from death, this will destroy it, requiring you to find §oanother § §fwoodland mansion. To avoid this, you would want to store your Totem of Undying somewhere after you get it. Unfortunately, you cannot craft Chests yet.

Some of the components require access to the Nether. In order to do this, you will need a Nether Portal. Obsidian can be found naturally in village blacksmith chests. You will then need to create a portal. 10 Obsidian should be sufficient.

There are other ways to make a Nether Portal. One could use buckets of water and lava in order to fill out the outline of a portal. However, you can't craft a bucket at this stage. You will need to loot a dungeon or woodland mansion, braving any monsters within. Then you can start using the bucket to make the portal.
You will need to fill your bucket with lava and water in order to make a portal. This requires a lot of precision, so you should use a cheap, non-flammable block in order to aid your efforts.

There are 3 more components for the Ultimate Crafting Table. They all require the Nether.

You will have to light the portal using fire, led through wood blocks from a nearby lava lake. This is the only controllable way to light the portal.

Then, for the next few components, you will need to brave the horrors of the Nether.

It is really going to suck to be you.

The easiest component (of those that require the Nether) is a Blaze Rod. You just have to find a nether fortress and kill a blaze, hoping that it drops a Blaze Rod. This should be very easy to accomplish, and there is almost no risk of death.

Oh who am I kidding, this will still be extremely difficult.

Another component is Nether Quartz. It is a lot tougher to get, as you cannot craft pickaxes required to mine it yet. You will need to attract the help of a ghast, and hope that its shot is on target to blow up the Nether Quartz Ore. You will also need to avoid being killed by the ghast's attacks.

The final component is a Nether Star. You will need to spawn and kill a Wither in order to acquire this item. This will be a very hard battle, due to your lack of good equipment and the sheer power of the Wither. The Wither will most likely kill you, but if you can somehow survive this battle, you will get the final component required to make an Ultimate Crafting Table.

You have finally acquired the resources needed to make an Ultimate Crafting Table. This will allow you to craft 9x9 recipes, opening up the entire tech tree of Minecraft to you. Hopefully you haven't lost any of the components during your travels.
Yeah, you are going to need A LOT of logs for this pack. You need 81 for a single plank.

When you are able to craft a plank, you will realize how brutal the recipes in this pack are, if you hadn't realized that already. 

Yes, 99% of the recipes are like this.

Yup, in order to craft a stick, you need 9 wood planks. That equates to 729 wood logs.

Good luck. 

You seriously should make a tree farm now.
Yeah, this is the most expensive wood tool, since it needs 8 sticks and 17 wood planks. However, this is vital for progression, since it can mine stone.
Let's be honest, a wooden axe isn't worth it. It will run out of durability before you can replace it. Then again, you can say that for half the tools in this pack.
You can craft a wood shovel, and the recipe is relatively cheap compared to some of the other wood tool recipes. However, that isn't saying much.
You can use the wooden hoe to make a farm. Then you can have a semi-reliable source of food. However, it won't be very big, since the wooden hoe is still quite expensive.
A wooden sword will be useful to you during combat. However, it won't be useful for long, as the low durability may cause it to break during combat.

You are going to need a lot of cobblestone for this pack. Unfortunately, the wood pickaxe only has 60 uses.

This is really going to suck for you.

In order to craft things out of stone, you will need to use Compressed Cobblestone, made out of 81 Cobblestone.

Yes, this will be very grindy.

In order to make stone tools, you will need to craft a Stone Toolmaker. This is very expensive, due to the costs in Compressed Cobblestone and all 5 wood tools. You should probably start some sort of mine, even though you won't be able to harvest many things due to the weakness of your wood tools.
Things are going to get exponentially more expensive from here on out. This is likely the easiest stone tool to craft, but that knowledge certainly won't save you.
The main use of this is for crafting. You certainly won't be getting 8 million wood from this.
Another item more useful for crafting than for its intended use.
This should increase the size of your farm, making you less likely to die of starvation.

For the cost of ridiculous amounts of wood and cobblestone, you can get an extra damage point on your sword!

yayyyyyyyyy *dies inside*
Now that you have a stone pickaxe, you can mine iron ore. In order to get it into a usable state, you have to take it through a long series of processes, so that you can use it for equipment.

You must craft a Furnace in order to proceed with the pack. While it cannot process iron directly, due to its limitations, it is a key component of the machine that can process iron ore, the Forge. It is able to melt iron ore into molten iron, which can be casted into iron nuggets.
You need a Forge in order to process iron ore into molten iron. It can reach temperatures high enough to melt the ore into liquid.
Melting iron ore is the first step in processing it into usable materials.

After a long and arduous task of processing and crafting, you can finally cast an iron nugget.

Unfortunately, to make iron usable, you must use iron blocks to make steel nuggets.
You must craft a Metal Former in order to proceed. This turns molten metal into various shapes, using casts.
Terracotta is one of the components for many of the machines required to process iron ore into a usable version.
In order to cool down molten metal enough to make it usable, you must find a way to make Blue Ice. The Freezer is used to accomplish this.
Blue Ice is required for cooling down molten metal. It is very expensive to make, since it requires you to turn snowballs to ice, ice to packed ice, and packed ice to blue ice.
You must make Castmakers in order to construct casts. These allow metal to cool into specific shapes. You must use Placeholder Clay and Clay in order to construct a working cast.
The first cast you will make is a Raw Nugget Cast. However, raw casts aren't usable, so you will have to find some way to turn it into a usable cast.
By using Furnaces, you can make casts usable for the Metal Former. This one is used to make metal nuggets.
Cobblestone to Dirt
Dirt to Coarse Dirt
Cobblestone to Sand
Sand to Red Sand
Dirt to Gravel
Sand to Clay
Yup, you need iron blocks to get steel. Good luck.
You need to construct a new type of brick, out of compressed soul sand and nether bricks. You need this to make a Blast Furnace, for turning iron into steel.
You must create a Blast Furnace to make steel. It is very expensive, blah blah blah.
Compressed Cobblestone to Lapis Lazuli
Gold Ore to Diamond
Diamond to Obsidian
Gold Ore to Redstone
Diamond to Emerald
Obsidian to Nether Quartz
You need a bunch of Bricks in order to make Coke Oven Bricks for a Coke Oven. You need this for making steel, as it is required to make coal coke, a vital component of steel.
Cobblestone to Netherrack
Netherrack to Soul Sand
These special bricks are required to create a Coke Oven, which is needed for Coal Coke.
You can finally make the Coke Oven, required for making Coal Coke, a catalyst for steel production.
You are finally able to make Coal Coke. Now, once you make a Blast Furnace, you can create steel.
You are finally able to create molten steel, using the Blast Furnace, with Coal Coke, Gunpowder, Blaze Rods, and Glowstone as reactants.
Now that you have molten steel, you can finally create steel nuggets.
Once you craft a Steel Toolmaker, you will be able to make Steel Tools.

While Steel tools are made of steel, they technically say they are made of iron. Ignore that, as, for all purposes, these are steel tools.

You need a Steel (Iron) Pickaxe in order to mine Gold.
The Steel Shovel is another tool that is probably useless except for crafting.
The main benefit of this sword is that it does slightly more damage. However, it's ridiculously expensive, and likely the most expensive steel tool.
A Steel Axe will give you some bonuses in terms of mining trees. However, the durability makes it not worth the steep cost.

Let's be honest. Is this really useful?

Probably not.

You will need gold to make the next tier of tools.




The quest title should describe what you have to be to get to this point.

Congratulations.

You have beaten the hardest modpack in all of existence. You have presevered through obstacles most players wouldn't stand a chance against. You have crafted the decillions of items necessary to win, and, when all odds were against you, defeated the evil Ender Dragon. Your monumental victory over the hardest modpack is shown, as you have finally won. You are free.
In order to make leather armor, you need a Leather Armormaker. It is made of reinforced leather blocks mainly, requiring lots and lots of leather, through several 9x9 recipes.
The leather helmet is craftable using the Leather Armormaker, but is one of the more expensive pieces of leather armor.
For some reason, the leather chestplate is the cheapest piece of leather armor.
Leather leggings are cheaper than a leather helmet, but more expensive than a leather chestplate.
For some reason, these are the most expensive piece of leather armor.
You need to make a Glass Production Oven in order to make molten glass. It uses blaze rods and coal coke as fuel.
Now you can melt glass into molten glass.
You must craft a Block Basin in order to turn molten glass into glass.
You can cast molten glass into glass, using the Block Basin. Blue Ice is required for it to work.
You must create a Breaking Chamber in order to smash blocks into shards, shards into crystals, and crystals into blades. You may use the blades for various purposes, due to their sharpness.
You must use the Breaking Chamber to convert glass into various forms. You can use the Glass Blades to make a Glass Cutter, used to turn glass into glass panes.
You can use the Breaking Chamber to smash Steel Blocks into blades, usable to make a Steel Cutter for making iron bars.
By using the glass and steel cutters, you can make glass panes and iron bars. You can craft these into Iron Bars, usable for making chains and chainmail armor.
You need to make a Chainmail Armormaker in order to craft leather armor.
